stories.Q4_2005: Users began seeding torrents in the forums in late 2005. The seeding activity grew at a slow rate for the next few quarters--perhaps fittingly, the most active forum was Computer Books.

stories.Q2_2007:
In the second quarter of 2007, seeding activity broke the 100-seeds/quarter mark for Computer Books and Collection of Books and Libraries, with the latter in the lead.

The other forums were gradually grew more active, and in the last quarter of 2007, Computer Books and The Exact and Natural Sciences, Engineering broke the 200-seeds/quarter mark.

stories.Q1_2013: In the first quarter of 2013, History of Science was the top forum and the first forum to break the 1,000-seed/quarter mark in over a year.
stories.total_seeds:
The top five rutracker.org forums by total seed count are The Exact and Natural Sciences, Engineering, Humanities, Collectibles, Interests, and Hobbies, History of Science, and Computer Books. Moving through time, we see this pattern is fairly consistent.

This hints at what is suspected/arguably already established: textual piracy is strongly driven in many cases by scholarly needs and the desire to access specialized, and often typically otherwise pricey, information.
